into all of that.

49
00:02:25,331 --> 00:02:27,933
I'm gonna start with some context.

50
00:02:28,594 --> 00:02:29,734
So we're all on the same page.

51
00:02:30,095 --> 00:02:34,038
So this is some fancy numbers about the games industry.

52
00:02:34,498 --> 00:02:37,240
Basically, the games industry today is really, really big.

53
00:02:38,481 --> 00:02:42,444
Last year generated about $140 billion in revenue.

54
00:02:43,564 --> 00:02:45,826
That makes it really one of the biggest

55
00:02:45,986 --> 00:02:47,667
entertainment industries in the world,

56
00:02:47,727 --> 00:02:50,449
far outpacing things like film and television

57
00:02:50,469 --> 00:02:52,371
and most other traditional media.

58
00:02:53,193 --> 00:02:54,994
There's two billion gamers in the world.

59
00:02:55,355 --> 00:03:00,838
What that means is two billion people touch games on a regular basis in the world.

60
00:03:00,898 --> 00:03:04,000
So that also, of course, expands to being global.

61
00:03:04,080 --> 00:03:05,501
Games are everywhere.

62
00:03:05,662 --> 00:03:07,383
Pretty much everywhere you go in the world,

63
00:03:07,723 --> 00:03:10,685
you're going to find games and even more specifically,

64
00:03:10,965 --> 00:03:12,266
video games of some kind.

65
00:03:13,267 --> 00:03:14,848
Now, you're all in the video games industry,

66
00:03:14,888 --> 00:03:16,569
so you probably know this already.

67
00:03:17,750 --> 00:03:19,371
This may seem like, yes, of course,

68
00:03:19,451 --> 00:03:21,152
games are a big deal. Of course, they are.

69
00:03:22,578 --> 00:03:27,800
This, if you've been in the industry for a while, you know that this has not been true up until

70
00:03:27,840 --> 00:03:33,702
pretty recently actually, and games have changed a lot in the last 30 years. So this is just a

71
00:03:33,722 --> 00:03:40,204
graph looking at the size of the industry. We're just sort of using revenue as one thing to look

72
00:03:40,244 --> 00:03:45,266
at the size of the industry, but it's, I think, tells a pretty compelling story. The industry has

73
00:03:45,906 --> 00:03:48,647
seen exponential growth in the last 20 years.

74
00:03:49,696 --> 00:03:53,978
So, you know, there's a little up and down starting in the 70s and 80s,

75
00:03:54,318 --> 00:03:57,579
but really it starts to explode right around the turn of the century.

76
00:03:58,240 --> 00:04:04,002
And that growth in gaming is intrinsically linked to the growth of connectivity in the internet.

77
00:04:04,863 --> 00:04:09,765
And that sort of led to this big boom in gaming, which also subsequently led to this big explosion

78
00:04:09,805 --> 00:04:13,646
in mobile games, which is sort of see that part of the industry get bigger and bigger and bigger

79
00:04:14,587 --> 00:04:18,469
as mobile games and internet, you know, internet connectivity, even in our pocket,

80
00:04:18,509 --> 00:04:19,489
goes up and up and up.

81
00:04:20,321 --> 00:04:24,102
So this reality that games industry growth

82
00:04:24,182 --> 00:04:27,583
is intrinsically connected to the growth of the internet

83
00:04:28,003 --> 00:04:30,704
has led to this narrative about the games industry

84
00:04:30,764 --> 00:04:32,585
that's really deeply impacted

85
00:04:32,605 --> 00:04:34,585
the way that we approach game design,

86
00:04:34,905 --> 00:04:36,586
especially in the last 10 years.

87
00:04:37,166 --> 00:04:40,387
And that narrative is that this growth was unlocked

88
00:04:40,687 --> 00:04:44,288
when we shifted our design focus from games as a product,

89
00:04:44,548 --> 00:04:46,569
right, these are discrete packaged goods

90
00:04:46,589 --> 00:04:48,009
that are designed to be consumed,

91
00:04:48,665 --> 00:04:51,507
And instead we started thinking of them as services.

92
00:04:51,907 --> 00:04:54,349
So evolving applications that are designed

93
00:04:54,389 --> 00:04:56,971
to be engaged with over and over and over again.

94
00:04:58,412 --> 00:05:01,374
So this narrative is pretty compelling, right?

95
00:05:01,414 --> 00:05:03,655
When we look at the industry today,

96
00:05:04,095 --> 00:05:06,497
we do see that this shift has happened.

97
00:05:07,318 --> 00:05:09,679
And when we look at the most successful games today,

98
00:05:10,000 --> 00:05:12,501
they're very rarely product style games.

99
00:05:12,862 --> 00:05:15,483
And so that also makes sense with this narrative.

100
00:05:15,907 --> 00:05:20,891
If we look at the top grossing games worldwide from 2017 to 2018,

101
00:05:21,392 --> 00:05:26,136
we see a list full of games that have service components.

102
00:05:26,496 --> 00:05:30,399
And I think what really drives this point home is when we look at the fact

103
00:05:30,860 --> 00:05:33,862
that these games are actually very similar in 2018 as they were in 2019.

104
00:05:33,942 --> 00:05:36,465
And we're still kind of sorting out the details of 2019, but I think it's...

105
00:05:43,979 --> 00:05:49,321
Fair to say that almost certainly 2019 will share many of the same games as well.

106
00:05:49,881 --> 00:05:53,142
And this really speaks to the idea that these games are not consumed media.

107
00:05:53,182 --> 00:05:56,404
They are really meant to be played over and over and over again.

108
00:05:56,424 --> 00:06:01,866
And in fact, every single game on this list has a service component.

109
00:06:02,266 --> 00:06:07,188
And many of them are also mobile, which sort of speaks to the state of the industry today

110
00:06:07,248 --> 00:06:09,589
and the way that the industry is composed today.

111
00:06:10,076 --> 00:06:12,797
So that all seems to make a lot of sense, right?

112
00:06:12,897 --> 00:06:15,298
So this growth really does come from this shift

113
00:06:15,738 --> 00:06:18,799
in design focus, from product to service.

114
00:06:19,379 --> 00:06:21,179
My problem with this narrative

115
00:06:21,579 --> 00:06:23,740
is that it isn't really about design.

116
00:06:23,860 --> 00:06:27,161
Even though a lot of times design gets cited

117
00:06:27,641 --> 00:06:29,422
in this narrative, in our shifting focus,

118
00:06:29,782 --> 00:06:31,262
it isn't a design narrative.

119
00:06:31,482 --> 00:06:33,723
This is actually a business narrative.

120
00:06:34,023 --> 00:06:37,324
This is a story of how our business focus changed

121
00:06:37,664 --> 00:06:38,664
over the last 20 years.

122
00:06:40,343 --> 00:06:43,906
And you can see that when we look at these two approaches, right?

123
00:06:43,926 --> 00:06:47,448
And we look at what it really means to be games as a product,

124
00:06:47,728 --> 00:06:49,569
and then what it means to be games as a service.

125
00:06:49,949 --> 00:06:53,091
These philosophies really speak to how games are delivered,

126
00:06:53,511 --> 00:06:55,032
not how they are designed.

127
00:06:55,412 --> 00:06:58,354
The two approaches definitely suggest things about design,

128
00:06:58,394 --> 00:07:01,816
and I think we can all imagine games that really only work

129
00:07:02,036 --> 00:07:04,898
in one category or another.

130
00:07:05,498 --> 00:07:08,320
But they're more...

131
00:07:09,550 --> 00:07:13,372
about the way the game is sort of delivered to players

132
00:07:13,513 --> 00:07:16,295
and the kind of business you're going to do with the game

133
00:07:16,735 --> 00:07:19,977
and a lot less about really what the game is.

134
00:07:20,838 --> 00:07:25,341
Even so, more and more game teams are being asked every day to

135
00:07:25,861 --> 00:07:29,804
make games as a service games. Even design teams are told

136
00:07:30,104 --> 00:07:34,367
design a game that's going to be a games as a service, design a game that's going

137
00:07:34,407 --> 00:07:38,870
to last forever. Things like that are being asked of these teams.

138
00:07:39,291 --> 00:07:42,512
because there's this idea that games as a service

139
00:07:43,213 --> 00:07:45,314
tells us all kinds of things about design,

140
00:07:45,734 --> 00:07:47,915
but there's a huge limitation

141
00:07:48,355 --> 00:07:51,737
to trying to apply a business strategy to game design.

142
00:07:52,137 --> 00:07:53,598
And I think we're starting to see that,

143
00:07:53,618 --> 00:07:56,119
a little bit of friction happen there

144
00:07:56,619 --> 00:08:00,001
between sort of player expectations,

145
00:08:00,781 --> 00:08:04,403
disconnects between what the game delivers

146
00:08:04,443 --> 00:08:05,883
and what sort of players expect.

147
00:08:06,243 --> 00:08:07,884
And a lot of that I think can be traced back

148
00:08:07,924 --> 00:08:08,905
to attempting to sort of.

149
00:08:09,528 --> 00:08:12,868
force design through this business lens.

150
00:08:14,169 --> 00:08:16,089
When we look at games as a service,

151
00:08:16,809 --> 00:08:18,249
they tell us, it tells us a lot,

152
00:08:18,309 --> 00:08:19,950
games as a service has a lot to say,

153
00:08:20,350 --> 00:08:23,750
but it's primarily focused on good service quality

154
00:08:24,090 --> 00:08:26,331
and optimizing experiences through iteration.

155
00:08:26,751 --> 00:08:29,031
What it doesn't really have is a lot to say

156
00:08:29,191 --> 00:08:31,352
about what those experiences should be.

157
00:08:32,272 --> 00:08:33,592
We don't really get a lot of clues

158
00:08:34,352 --> 00:08:35,712
about how to design the game

159
00:08:35,752 --> 00:08:37,172
by looking at games as a service.

160
00:08:37,693 --> 00:08:38,873
Right, games as a service says.

161
00:08:39,329 --> 00:08:41,731
Be reliable, deliver valuable services.

162
00:08:41,951 --> 00:08:43,692
Awesome, that's a really great message.

163
00:08:44,072 --> 00:08:46,294
But what services should be delivered?

164
00:08:46,494 --> 00:08:47,155
We don't really know.

165
00:08:47,175 --> 00:08:49,776
Then it says polish and iterate those experiences.

166
00:08:49,977 --> 00:08:52,318
Again, a fantastic thing to try to do.

167
00:08:52,338 --> 00:08:53,239
It's a good process.

168
00:08:53,579 --> 00:08:55,340
But what experiences are we polishing

169
00:08:55,701 --> 00:08:57,302
and what are we iterating towards?

170
00:08:58,362 --> 00:08:59,583
And then it says, you know,

171
00:08:59,683 --> 00:09:02,425
drive towards KPIs or key performance indicators, right?

172
00:09:02,525 --> 00:09:04,927
Pick targets of things you want to drive towards.

173
00:09:05,347 --> 00:09:06,908
Great, we should all do that.

174
00:09:07,129 --> 00:09:08,630
But which ones and why?

175
00:09:09,282 --> 00:09:12,683
You know, design has to ask these questions.

176
00:09:12,703 --> 00:09:14,843
These are fundamentally the questions of design.

177
00:09:15,143 --> 00:09:18,064
What services, what experiences, why are we doing this?

178
00:09:18,144 --> 00:09:19,224
What are we driving towards?

179
00:09:19,544 --> 00:09:22,625
And games as a service just doesn't really have the answers.

180
00:09:22,705 --> 00:09:25,185
It has processes, but it doesn't really tell us

181
00:09:25,645 --> 00:09:26,726
what we're trying to do.

182
00:09:28,246 --> 00:09:30,606
Besides, really successful game designs

183
00:09:30,706 --> 00:09:32,507
are not centered around services.

184
00:09:32,887 --> 00:09:33,827
I think we all know that.

185
00:09:34,047 --> 00:09:35,727
They're supported by services,

186
00:09:35,907 --> 00:09:37,648
and they're supported by this kind of thinking

187
00:09:37,688 --> 00:09:38,548
and this kind of process.

188
00:09:38,864 --> 00:09:41,346
but they're not built around those services.

189
00:09:41,786 --> 00:09:43,467
If design puts service first,

190
00:09:43,847 --> 00:09:46,109
it can result in really polished,

191
00:09:46,329 --> 00:09:49,551
but often soulless games, or even worse,

192
00:09:49,871 --> 00:09:53,153
coldly efficient engagement extraction machines

193
00:09:53,433 --> 00:09:54,954
that don't really connect with players

194
00:09:55,014 --> 00:09:57,916
on any kind of deep emotional or motivational level.

195
00:09:58,717 --> 00:10:01,198
Games as a service just doesn't provide designers

196
00:10:01,278 --> 00:10:02,939
with what they need to understand

197
00:10:02,999 --> 00:10:04,380
how to make great live games.

198
00:10:04,640 --> 00:10:07,442
It's just missing a lot in that area.

199
00:10:08,382 --> 00:10:09,862
If we look back at this list,

200
00:10:10,723 --> 00:10:12,423
it is true that all of these games

201
00:10:12,663 --> 00:10:14,564
use a games as a service business model,

202
00:10:15,505 --> 00:10:16,645
and that's great,

203
00:10:16,945 --> 00:10:19,006
but what's more important for designers

204
00:10:19,046 --> 00:10:20,907
looking at this game is not their business model.

205
00:10:21,167 --> 00:10:23,268
What's more important is that all of these games

206
00:10:23,328 --> 00:10:25,809
are designed around intrinsic motivations,

207
00:10:26,309 --> 00:10:28,710
rich experiences that evolve and change over time,

208
00:10:29,111 --> 00:10:30,871
and long-term engagement that can become

209
00:10:30,891 --> 00:10:32,032
a part of a player's life.

210
00:10:32,632 --> 00:10:34,693
That's what we should really be taking

211
00:10:35,033 --> 00:10:36,714
from these games' success.

212
00:10:37,218 --> 00:10:40,659
the ability to become more than just consumed media.

213
00:10:40,979 --> 00:10:43,360
That's what keeps these games at the top of this list

214
00:10:43,580 --> 00:10:46,381
from the player's perspective, year over year.

215
00:10:46,901 --> 00:10:49,041
And some of these games like League of Legends

216
00:10:49,301 --> 00:10:51,662
or Dungeon and Fighter Online,

217
00:10:52,082 --> 00:10:53,703
they've been at the top of this list

218
00:10:54,023 --> 00:10:56,003
long before we started talking about

219
00:10:56,023 --> 00:10:58,024
games as a service at GDC.

220
00:10:58,924 --> 00:11:02,825
They've been doing this with a sort of different approach

221
00:11:02,905 --> 00:11:05,266
before we started categorizing things

222
00:11:05,366 --> 00:11:06,327
as games as a service.

223
00:11:07,430 --> 00:11:09,851
This might seem like a fine line that I'm drawing here,

224
00:11:09,871 --> 00:11:13,091
this difference between this business approach

225
00:11:13,651 --> 00:11:15,512
and this design approach,

226
00:11:15,832 --> 00:11:18,992
this difference between focusing on optimizing service

227
00:11:19,332 --> 00:11:21,673
and focusing on long-term player experiences.

228
00:11:21,993 --> 00:11:23,553
That might seem like a really fine line,

229
00:11:23,593 --> 00:11:26,074
but in my experience, it can be incredibly striking.

230
00:11:26,574 --> 00:11:29,394
So as an example, I just wanna talk a little bit

231
00:11:29,434 --> 00:11:32,215
about some of the things that we saw in Guild Wars 2.

232
00:11:32,555 --> 00:11:35,275
So these are really scrubbed numbers from Guild Wars 2.

233
00:11:35,435 --> 00:11:35,755
They're just-

234
00:11:36,118 --> 00:11:43,461
relational and what we're looking at is average revenue per user and retention numbers and on the

235
00:11:43,521 --> 00:11:50,984
left we just have all players. So everyone playing Guild Wars 2 this is this is the average or mean

236
00:11:51,225 --> 00:12:00,409
of the ARPU and retention for these players and it's fine but on the right we have cohort number

