00:13:01,907 --> 00:13:03,787
You do not need to go to town to do these things.

258
00:13:03,807 --> 00:13:06,869
There's very little in the game,

259
00:13:06,909 --> 00:13:09,610
in the game loop that drives players to town.

260
00:13:10,050 --> 00:13:13,271
And yet, spending time in town is clearly super important.

261
00:13:14,371 --> 00:13:17,813
And if we dig into this, it's not an outlier group, right?

262
00:13:17,873 --> 00:13:20,134
If we just narrow down all the players

263
00:13:20,314 --> 00:13:22,214
that are engaged in the game,

264
00:13:22,234 --> 00:13:24,075
so players are actually actively playing the game,

265
00:13:24,095 --> 00:13:28,197
excuse me, we see that actually

266
00:13:28,217 --> 00:13:29,457
a majority of them are townies.

267
00:13:29,994 --> 00:13:31,334
a lot of them spend time in town.

268
00:13:31,895 --> 00:13:34,576
And if we dig deeper in this curve on the right,

269
00:13:34,937 --> 00:13:37,839
you can see the likelihood of being a townie grows

270
00:13:38,339 --> 00:13:40,580
over the player's first 100 days playing the game.

271
00:13:41,621 --> 00:13:43,642
Even though the amount of things to do in town

272
00:13:43,662 --> 00:13:46,024
does not increase as you progress in the game,

273
00:13:46,684 --> 00:13:48,065
and certainly not to this level.

274
00:13:48,085 --> 00:13:52,228
And this increasing tendency to spend time in town

275
00:13:52,608 --> 00:13:54,910
corresponds with this increasing likelihood

276
00:13:54,930 --> 00:13:55,730
to become a spender.

277
00:13:56,774 --> 00:13:59,275
So really for us, just being a great highly engaged player

278
00:13:59,335 --> 00:14:00,735
seems to be strongly correlated

279
00:14:00,775 --> 00:14:02,275
with spending this time in town.

280
00:14:03,936 --> 00:14:06,056
I don't really find this particularly surprising,

281
00:14:06,076 --> 00:14:09,417
mostly because we saw a really similar effect

282
00:14:09,557 --> 00:14:11,478
in MapleStory when I was working on that.

283
00:14:11,978 --> 00:14:14,258
So this wasn't a huge shock to me

284
00:14:15,319 --> 00:14:19,240
because spending time in towns and non-combat social zones

285
00:14:19,640 --> 00:14:21,580
usually means focusing on social interactions

286
00:14:21,600 --> 00:14:22,680
like chatting and voting

287
00:14:23,160 --> 00:14:24,941
or simply being seen by other players.

288
00:14:25,337 --> 00:14:27,618
And it also means downtime, which can be really important

289
00:14:27,998 --> 00:14:30,659
for players that are trying to spend a lot of time

290
00:14:30,699 --> 00:14:33,120
in your game to not always be actively engaged,

291
00:14:33,140 --> 00:14:35,441
but to have some downtime where they can relax and plan

292
00:14:35,461 --> 00:14:36,702
and just sort of talk.

293
00:14:39,143 --> 00:14:42,044
Design, the point I'm making in bringing this up, right,

294
00:14:42,184 --> 00:14:43,504
is the design has to be thinking

295
00:14:43,564 --> 00:14:44,765
about the player's experience

296
00:14:44,805 --> 00:14:47,526
and what's engaging to them in the game,

297
00:14:47,546 --> 00:14:49,046
and what kind of experiences and engagement

298
00:14:49,086 --> 00:14:50,307
the game is giving to them,

299
00:14:50,767 --> 00:14:52,728
not just how to engage them more.

300
00:14:53,150 --> 00:14:55,551
If we focus too much on just delivering services,

301
00:14:55,972 --> 00:15:00,294
we might just get bogged down in just increasing engagement.

302
00:15:00,314 --> 00:15:02,535
You know, both Guild Wars 2 and MapleStory

303
00:15:02,575 --> 00:15:04,716
have lots of progression systems and rewards

304
00:15:04,756 --> 00:15:08,858
and gameplay loops and combat and all of these things

305
00:15:08,898 --> 00:15:10,718
that we associate with active engagement.

306
00:15:11,619 --> 00:15:13,900
And we can spend a lot of time trying to increase

307
00:15:14,220 --> 00:15:16,201
players' engagement with those systems.

308
00:15:16,541 --> 00:15:18,502
But what we actually saw was that as players

309
00:15:18,542 --> 00:15:19,923
invested more time in the game,

310
00:15:20,163 --> 00:15:22,704
they were more motivated by relatedness.

311
00:15:23,445 --> 00:15:26,645
to other players and the joy of wasting time just chatting in town.

312
00:15:27,306 --> 00:15:30,366
Now, I'm not saying that every game should add social spaces to increase revenue

313
00:15:30,426 --> 00:15:34,747
or that there's some magic connection between spending downtime in town

314
00:15:34,867 --> 00:15:38,668
and spending in every game, but I just want to emphasize that engagement

315
00:15:38,728 --> 00:15:43,449
is more likely to come from the actions that feed whatever the game's intrinsic motivator is,

316
00:15:43,829 --> 00:15:49,050
not necessarily the actions that feed really easy-to-measure and optimized loops.

317
00:15:50,151 --> 00:15:51,331
For MapleStory and Guild Wars 2,

318
00:15:51,990 --> 00:15:53,992
The motivators in the game, and we already knew this,

319
00:15:54,112 --> 00:15:56,554
are largely social, they're largely relatedness.

320
00:15:56,914 --> 00:15:58,575
For other games, it's going to be other things,

321
00:15:58,815 --> 00:16:01,597
but the point is, design has to think about those things

322
00:16:01,677 --> 00:16:03,338
from that direction, from the direction of

323
00:16:03,358 --> 00:16:05,100
what are the player experience going to be

324
00:16:05,440 --> 00:16:06,521
and what's going to motivate them,

325
00:16:06,881 --> 00:16:09,843
not just from the direction of how is my service optimized?

326
00:16:12,425 --> 00:16:15,147
So, Games as a Service, it's been really great for business,

327
00:16:15,207 --> 00:16:16,428
it's been great for strategy.

328
00:16:16,608 --> 00:16:18,509
I think it does actually have a lot to offer

329
00:16:18,890 --> 00:16:19,890
to game development.

330
00:16:20,276 --> 00:16:22,536
as far as processes and just a way of thinking

331
00:16:22,576 --> 00:16:24,257
about delivering to players,

332
00:16:24,677 --> 00:16:27,978
but it's mostly confusing and frustrating for design

333
00:16:28,018 --> 00:16:30,278
because it just doesn't fit into the things

334
00:16:30,298 --> 00:16:31,278
that we're trying to do.

335
00:16:31,778 --> 00:16:34,479
And yet more and more teams will continue to be asked

336
00:16:34,539 --> 00:16:36,939
to make engagement-focused live games, right?

337
00:16:36,959 --> 00:16:38,940
We want to make engagement-focused live games,

338
00:16:39,320 --> 00:16:43,121
but Games as a Service isn't really gonna help design

339
00:16:43,161 --> 00:16:45,461
because it doesn't really show us any design direction.

340
00:16:46,582 --> 00:16:48,982
Luckily, there is an approach to game development

341
00:16:49,002 --> 00:16:49,722
that's been around.

342
00:16:50,105 --> 00:16:54,508
For a long time, it's been employed by those working in live games for quite a long time,

343
00:16:54,848 --> 00:16:58,390
and it is a lot more useful for game design,

344
00:16:58,650 --> 00:17:03,193
and I think it has a lot more to say about the direction of design.

345
00:17:03,574 --> 00:17:06,175
And that is, of course, LiveOps. Surprise.

346
00:17:07,616 --> 00:17:14,241
So LiveOps is a way of thinking about game design and game service

347
00:17:14,501 --> 00:17:16,162
that's been around since...

348
00:17:17,324 --> 00:17:18,985
MUDs, which are multi-user dungeons.

349
00:17:19,025 --> 00:17:21,486
These are sort of the precursors to MMOs.

350
00:17:21,526 --> 00:17:25,647
They were text-based multiplayer adventures

351
00:17:26,267 --> 00:17:28,648
that were around in the 80s, largely in 90s.

352
00:17:29,688 --> 00:17:31,809
And that's sort of where LiveOps grew up,

353
00:17:32,189 --> 00:17:35,450
was in managing these online communities

354
00:17:35,510 --> 00:17:37,771
of people playing MUDs together.

355
00:17:37,791 --> 00:17:41,532
And it's great, LiveOps, is it's supporting games

356
00:17:41,792 --> 00:17:43,352
that are focused on long-term engagement.

357
00:17:43,372 --> 00:17:44,893
Because it's sort of what it grew out of.

358
00:17:45,766 --> 00:17:46,866
At the heart of LiveOps,

359
00:17:47,227 --> 00:17:49,168
it's really about taking care of a game

360
00:17:49,708 --> 00:17:51,449
and taking care of the game's players

361
00:17:51,910 --> 00:17:53,471
over an extended period of time.

362
00:17:53,511 --> 00:17:55,172
So you can see that in the word itself.

363
00:17:55,632 --> 00:17:58,714
It's live, it's connected experience, it's persistent,

364
00:17:59,135 --> 00:18:00,596
and there's an operation component

365
00:18:00,936 --> 00:18:02,377
where you evolve and change

366
00:18:02,517 --> 00:18:04,398
and take care of it with continual investment.

367
00:18:05,919 --> 00:18:08,281
I have spent pretty much the entirety of my 17 years

368
00:18:08,321 --> 00:18:10,162
in the industry working in LiveOps frameworks.

369
00:18:10,202 --> 00:18:12,263
So a lot of experience with LiveOps.

370
00:18:12,604 --> 00:18:14,925
And I've seen the approach in my time go

371
00:18:15,442 --> 00:18:18,763
from mostly servicing relatively small niche communities

372
00:18:18,823 --> 00:18:21,184
in virtual worlds online,

373
00:18:21,504 --> 00:18:22,984
to being a big driving force

374
00:18:23,024 --> 00:18:24,305
behind the free to play explosion,

375
00:18:24,445 --> 00:18:26,146
and now having deep influence

376
00:18:26,446 --> 00:18:27,946
on some of the most successful games today,

377
00:18:28,046 --> 00:18:29,227
and also the AAA space.

378
00:18:29,587 --> 00:18:35,189
So LiveOps has grown in its importance

379
00:18:35,509 --> 00:18:36,709
to the game industry in general.

380
00:18:36,950 --> 00:18:39,010
And I will say, as I work with teams

381
00:18:39,110 --> 00:18:42,212
who are transitioning to thinking about making live games

382
00:18:42,712 --> 00:18:43,952
and service-based games,

383
00:18:44,996 --> 00:18:48,017
Teams that have some tradition of LiveOps

384
00:18:48,057 --> 00:18:50,017
or some understanding of live operations

385
00:18:50,358 --> 00:18:51,918
tend to be a little bit better prepared

386
00:18:52,358 --> 00:18:54,599
for what's coming when they make this transition.

387
00:18:54,619 --> 00:18:58,900
So that's LiveOps, but of course,

388
00:18:59,100 --> 00:19:00,801
we wanna know how do you do LiveOps?

