511
00:24:44,841 --> 00:24:46,342
and also some real-world timers.

512
00:24:46,742 --> 00:24:48,283
So when players are playing Guild Wars 2

513
00:24:48,343 --> 00:24:49,403
and they're out questing,

514
00:24:49,777 --> 00:24:51,877
They don't go get quests from NPCs.

515
00:24:52,277 --> 00:24:55,498
They actually just engage with whatever event

516
00:24:55,558 --> 00:24:57,419
is active in the area they're in at the time.

517
00:24:57,779 --> 00:25:00,460
And some of their actions might trigger an event to happen,

518
00:25:00,520 --> 00:25:02,080
or they might walk into an area

519
00:25:02,100 --> 00:25:03,760
where an event is already underway,

520
00:25:04,041 --> 00:25:06,921
or events might be designed to trigger automatically

521
00:25:07,301 --> 00:25:08,442
every X number of minutes.

522
00:25:08,742 --> 00:25:10,482
But the world is sort of this dynamic place

523
00:25:11,443 --> 00:25:13,663
where players are walking around and engaging with it.

524
00:25:14,203 --> 00:25:15,924
So the Guild Wars 2 content designers

525
00:25:16,244 --> 00:25:19,105
crafted the maps to be these branching chains of events.

526
00:25:19,578 --> 00:25:23,081
that are punctuated by fights with elite enemies called champions.

527
00:25:23,521 --> 00:25:28,324
The design was that players would play through a sort of emerging story of events

528
00:25:29,085 --> 00:25:30,686
that culminates in a boss fight, right?

529
00:25:30,706 --> 00:25:32,768
It was pretty traditional, it's just more dynamic.

530
00:25:34,009 --> 00:25:36,751
And that players would just sort of experience this inside of the map,

531
00:25:36,811 --> 00:25:38,832
probably in small groups or maybe even solo.

532
00:25:39,573 --> 00:25:42,455
So when the game launched, we had made all of our maps

533
00:25:42,996 --> 00:25:44,937
match sort of this philosophy, and then...

534
00:25:46,327 --> 00:25:50,349
nothing about our plan actually ended up working that way

535
00:25:50,409 --> 00:25:53,971
because players did not do what we expected them to do,

536
00:25:54,291 --> 00:25:54,871
shockingly.

537
00:25:56,652 --> 00:25:59,474
Instead, players coordinated over chat

538
00:25:59,734 --> 00:26:02,796
to form these large groups of 50 to 100 players

539
00:26:03,096 --> 00:26:06,017
that would roam the map as a devastating zerg

540
00:26:06,358 --> 00:26:07,658
in this efficient loop,

541
00:26:07,918 --> 00:26:10,120
defeating all the champions in succession.

542
00:26:10,960 --> 00:26:12,621
And they called this the champ train.

543
00:26:12,801 --> 00:26:13,661
And it didn't take long.

544
00:26:14,337 --> 00:26:16,598
for players to get these champ trains organized.

545
00:26:17,278 --> 00:26:21,199
The champ train ignored the intended story-driven loops

546
00:26:21,239 --> 00:26:23,700
of events and it removed a lot of the challenge

547
00:26:23,760 --> 00:26:25,020
that would come from battling bosses

548
00:26:25,060 --> 00:26:28,401
because the zerg of 100 players can simply steamroll

549
00:26:28,441 --> 00:26:29,761
basically everything in the map.

550
00:26:30,501 --> 00:26:33,202
And so this was really nothing

551
00:26:33,542 --> 00:26:35,903
like what the content designers had intended at all.

552
00:26:36,263 --> 00:26:38,663
And at first we tried to come up with ways

553
00:26:38,683 --> 00:26:41,004
to discourage this behavior and sort of force players.

554
00:26:41,374 --> 00:26:44,695
back into the intended track, move things around,

555
00:26:44,735 --> 00:26:46,056
separate it, disincentivize it.

556
00:26:46,496 --> 00:26:48,637
But the truth was, as we were playing the game too

557
00:26:48,797 --> 00:26:51,778
and listening to feedback, the chat train was really fun.

558
00:26:51,798 --> 00:26:54,019
And players actually really enjoyed it.

559
00:26:54,179 --> 00:26:54,939
It was a good time.

560
00:26:55,019 --> 00:26:57,140
It's fun to join a big zerg of players

561
00:26:57,180 --> 00:26:58,921
and just sort of steamroll over things

562
00:26:58,961 --> 00:27:03,402
and have all this sort of efficient move around the map.

563
00:27:03,842 --> 00:27:06,523
You can just sort of join up and follow along.

564
00:27:07,196 --> 00:27:13,577
And what we saw was actually players that participated had better engagement and the maps with good champ train sought more playtime.

565
00:27:13,597 --> 00:27:15,578
So players were really liking this.

566
00:27:16,098 --> 00:27:20,879
So we basically pretty quickly said, OK, we give in.

567
00:27:21,759 --> 00:27:24,540
This emergent behavior is actually a good thing.

568
00:27:24,720 --> 00:27:25,660
And we switched our approach.

569
00:27:26,200 --> 00:27:30,942
Instead of trying to stop the champ train, we asked, how do we make them as fun as possible for everyone?

570
00:27:31,853 --> 00:27:33,794
Ultimately what that meant was we relocated

571
00:27:33,854 --> 00:27:35,835
many of the champ trains away from starter zones.

572
00:27:35,875 --> 00:27:37,216
We sort of moved them around the map

573
00:27:37,256 --> 00:27:38,397
to keep them away from people

574
00:27:38,437 --> 00:27:39,877
who were just starting out in the game

575
00:27:39,897 --> 00:27:41,798
because that wasn't a fantastic experience for them.

576
00:27:42,899 --> 00:27:44,440
We added boss timers to the worlds

577
00:27:44,620 --> 00:27:46,080
for better coordination in the game.

578
00:27:46,861 --> 00:27:48,402
We adjusted many of the event loops

579
00:27:48,442 --> 00:27:50,403
to remove the incentive to fail events

580
00:27:50,423 --> 00:27:52,684
because previously some of those bosses

581
00:27:52,704 --> 00:27:53,724
that the champ train wanted to get

582
00:27:53,764 --> 00:27:55,525
could only happen if they failed an event,

583
00:27:55,565 --> 00:27:58,326
which was not great and would disrupt the story

584
00:27:58,346 --> 00:28:00,147
for people who were trying to consume the story.

585
00:28:01,678 --> 00:28:04,660
And we made a lot of adjustments to loot and loops

586
00:28:05,621 --> 00:28:06,862
and all of that great stuff.

587
00:28:07,863 --> 00:28:09,504
One thing this didn't solve was Champ Train

588
00:28:09,564 --> 00:28:11,466
still made boss battles pretty trivial,

589
00:28:11,826 --> 00:28:13,847
but we actually learned from this as well eventually.

590
00:28:14,388 --> 00:28:16,990
And we eventually actually used this to design

591
00:28:17,470 --> 00:28:20,473
really cool, challenging open world bosses

592
00:28:20,733 --> 00:28:22,214
that were meant to be played

593
00:28:22,274 --> 00:28:24,216
by like a group of 100 players at once.

594
00:28:24,256 --> 00:28:25,997
This is Dequadal, which is one of those

595
00:28:26,397 --> 00:28:28,439
first really large scale.

596
00:28:29,414 --> 00:28:31,755
bosses be added after the game was already live.

597
00:28:32,115 --> 00:28:33,355
It's meant to be played by a group,

598
00:28:33,595 --> 00:28:35,275
I think the optimal group is like 80,

599
00:28:36,475 --> 00:28:37,956
coordinating together to take them down.

600
00:28:39,516 --> 00:28:42,857
And so this was actually a big achievement for us

601
00:28:43,657 --> 00:28:45,917
in listening to player feedback and not reacting

602
00:28:45,937 --> 00:28:47,998
and trying to force them into the mold

603
00:28:48,038 --> 00:28:48,898
we thought they should be in,

604
00:28:48,918 --> 00:28:51,478
but actually going along with their emergent behavior

605
00:28:51,518 --> 00:28:52,979
and what they really enjoyed doing.

606
00:28:53,619 --> 00:28:56,459
But what's really important is that none of this

607
00:28:56,499 --> 00:28:59,040
would be possible if it hadn't been easy.

608
00:28:59,543 --> 00:29:03,167
for us to move things around, mess with boss timing,

609
00:29:03,427 --> 00:29:05,729
change balance rewards without breaking the structure

610
00:29:05,749 --> 00:29:06,610
of everything in the map.

611
00:29:07,010 --> 00:29:09,632
Because we knew before we launched the game

612
00:29:09,933 --> 00:29:12,235
that we would probably want to make changes to it

613
00:29:12,395 --> 00:29:13,716
after a lot of players were playing it,

614
00:29:14,176 --> 00:29:16,318
it was possible for us to make these changes.

615
00:29:16,619 --> 00:29:18,340
I'm not going to say it was trivial,

616
00:29:18,780 --> 00:29:20,142
but it was definitely doable,

617
00:29:20,222 --> 00:29:22,644
and we didn't have to worry about breaking the whole game

618
00:29:22,664 --> 00:29:24,946
because we were going to move around some quests.

619
00:29:27,762 --> 00:29:31,123
So the point of that just is that content

620
00:29:31,203 --> 00:29:32,723
is the first thing you want to think about.

621
00:29:32,903 --> 00:29:34,264
And while that does require some planning

622
00:29:34,284 --> 00:29:35,344
before you do the live game,

623
00:29:36,405 --> 00:29:38,185
in order to make it possible for you to iterate,

624
00:29:38,605 --> 00:29:40,326
you want to be focused in this point

625
00:29:40,486 --> 00:29:42,667
in your live ops journey on that iteration.

626
00:29:42,827 --> 00:29:44,187
Improve the game's performance,

627
00:29:44,307 --> 00:29:46,448
extend its life, respond to feedback.

628
00:29:47,008 --> 00:29:48,469
That is going to require that you also

629
00:29:48,789 --> 00:29:50,670
build some feedback management processes

630
00:29:51,070 --> 00:29:52,930
and also some live incident processes.

631
00:29:53,010 --> 00:29:54,411
So you're going to want to figure out

632
00:29:54,511 --> 00:29:55,992
how you want to take in that feedback.

633
00:29:56,963 --> 00:30:00,104
You can start by just reading forums or Reddit.

634
00:30:00,464 --> 00:30:03,365
That's probably going to give you a bit of a skewed perspective on things.

635
00:30:03,445 --> 00:30:07,186
So you might want to think a little more deeply about how you're going to process feedback as it comes in.

636
00:30:07,586 --> 00:30:10,727
Are you going to set up other channels for players to deliver that feedback to you?

637
00:30:11,047 --> 00:30:13,888
How are you going to handle the feedback coming from inside the team as well?

638
00:30:14,808 --> 00:30:19,349
And then, of course, live incident processes when inevitably something's going to go wrong.

639
00:30:19,689 --> 00:30:21,570
As you're iterating the game, you're going to make mistakes.

640
00:30:22,290 --> 00:30:23,910
Games are incredibly complicated and messy.

641
00:30:24,360 --> 00:30:25,781
and it's pretty much impossible to avoid.

642
00:30:25,801 --> 00:30:27,862
So what are you going to do when that happens?

643
00:30:28,402 --> 00:30:30,664
Hopefully not panic and hopefully respond in a way

644
00:30:30,704 --> 00:30:32,564
that's going to be healthy for your community.

645
00:30:33,085 --> 00:30:34,465
And finally, rounding this out

646
00:30:34,786 --> 00:30:36,206
is business intelligence tracking.

647
00:30:36,526 --> 00:30:37,587
I put this on here,

648
00:30:37,807 --> 00:30:40,048
even though it might not seem like a design area of focus,

649
00:30:40,328 --> 00:30:41,469
because in my experience,

650
00:30:42,129 --> 00:30:44,851
teams that are really good at this phase of live ops

651
00:30:45,171 --> 00:30:47,552
do have design take a larger role in that area.

652
00:30:47,812 --> 00:30:50,013
With all the iteration and feedback response going on,

653
00:30:50,253 --> 00:30:51,694
design really does need to be on top

654
00:30:51,714 --> 00:30:53,335
of how those changes are affecting the community

655
00:30:53,495 --> 00:30:54,095
and the business.

656
00:30:54,398 --> 00:30:57,019
to avoid conflicts where design wants to do one thing

657
00:30:57,920 --> 00:30:59,581
and business doesn't want to do that.

658
00:30:59,601 --> 00:31:01,682
So you really need to keep those guys close

659
00:31:02,583 --> 00:31:04,744
and working in concert in order to make this

660
00:31:05,265 --> 00:31:08,687
a more successful iterative process for your game.

661
00:31:10,228 --> 00:31:13,209
So awesome, live ops basics, you're iterating your game.

662
00:31:13,350 --> 00:31:14,510
If you can get good at this,

663
00:31:14,830 --> 00:31:17,752
if you can in fact iterate on your game

664
00:31:17,852 --> 00:31:20,634
without having to destroy the whole thing

665
00:31:20,674 --> 00:31:22,675
and you're making incremental improvements.

666
00:31:23,179 --> 00:31:25,740
And you get to this point where you start saying things like,

667
00:31:25,860 --> 00:31:30,262
man, I wish that we had a little bit more insight

668
00:31:30,302 --> 00:31:31,982
into which changes we want to make.

669
00:31:32,463 --> 00:31:35,003
Also, maybe some of the changes we want to make

670
00:31:35,164 --> 00:31:37,164
are good for some group of players, but not another.

671
00:31:37,504 --> 00:31:41,266
You're ready to move on to the second phase

672
00:31:41,546 --> 00:31:45,247
of LiveOps maturity, which is LiveOps optimizing

673
00:31:45,907 --> 00:31:48,688
with a focus on personalizing your player's experience.

674
00:31:50,888 --> 00:31:53,690
This is all about serving content and experiences

675
00:31:53,750 --> 00:31:56,592
to players based on who they are and how they behave,

676
00:31:56,912 --> 00:32:00,075
instead of just making blunt overall changes to the game.

677
00:32:00,655 --> 00:32:02,056
This is what most people are thinking of

678
00:32:02,076 --> 00:32:03,157
when they talk about gathering up

679
00:32:03,197 --> 00:32:04,458
tons of player behavior data.

680
00:32:05,078 --> 00:32:05,999
Right, they think like, yeah,

681
00:32:06,019 --> 00:32:08,241
we're gonna like do a bunch of segmentation

682
00:32:08,281 --> 00:32:10,062
and like analyze it,

683
00:32:10,122 --> 00:32:12,063
and then it's gonna tell us all kinds of cool stuff

684
00:32:12,083 --> 00:32:13,624
that we should do to the game to make it better.

685
00:32:15,226 --> 00:32:18,168
I do think a lot of teams try to do this step first,

686
00:32:18,664 --> 00:32:21,366
but I would suggest that it is very

687
00:32:21,426 --> 00:32:23,528
difficult to make this step work for

688
00:32:23,568 --> 00:32:25,849
you if you don't have the basics down,

689
00:32:26,170 --> 00:32:28,531
because data is only valuable if you

690
00:32:28,551 --> 00:32:29,892
can actually do something with it.

691
00:32:30,253 --> 00:32:33,335
So even if you collect lots of fantastic data,

692
00:32:33,575 --> 00:32:34,876
it can be really,

693
00:32:34,936 --> 00:32:36,937
really hard to action on it if you

694
00:32:36,977 --> 00:32:41,181
don't actually have the means to make

695
00:32:41,221 --> 00:32:42,922
those iterative changes into the game.

696
00:32:42,942 --> 00:32:46,905
OK, so we're optimizing.

697
00:32:48,048 --> 00:32:52,930
What does this really mean to a development team functionally?

698
00:32:52,950 --> 00:32:54,930
A lot of it is about segmentation.

699
00:32:55,650 --> 00:32:57,491
Segmentation, whether we're talking about

700
00:32:57,931 --> 00:32:59,752
segmenting by acquisition timing,

701
00:32:59,812 --> 00:33:02,213
like these players all joined the game in the same month,

702
00:33:02,293 --> 00:33:03,553
or these players all joined the game

703
00:33:03,993 --> 00:33:06,834
from the same marketing campaign.

704
00:33:07,194 --> 00:33:08,495
Or in-game behavior, right?

705
00:33:08,535 --> 00:33:11,536
These players only ever do PVP,

706
00:33:11,636 --> 00:33:14,617
and these players only ever do story content.

707
00:33:15,157 --> 00:33:16,918
Or player motivation, right?

708
00:33:16,998 --> 00:33:19,679
These players really will do anything

709
00:33:19,779 --> 00:33:23,201
that gets their progression to increase.

710
00:33:23,401 --> 00:33:24,821
Or these players will only do things

711
00:33:24,841 --> 00:33:25,682
that are socially motivated.

712
00:33:26,102 --> 00:33:27,382
All of these are segmentations

713
00:33:28,103 --> 00:33:30,704
that you can make to your players

714
00:33:30,904 --> 00:33:32,545
and look at them differently.

715
00:33:33,345 --> 00:33:35,186
And it can be an incredibly powerful tool

716
00:33:35,666 --> 00:33:37,947
in driving more targeted changes into your game.

717
00:33:40,028 --> 00:33:40,348
Excuse me.

718
00:33:41,767 --> 00:33:44,630
In phase one, teams tend to rely pretty much solely

719
00:33:44,830 --> 00:33:47,212
on just the design team's expertise,

720
00:33:47,612 --> 00:33:49,174
the things that you already know that you should do,

721
00:33:50,234 --> 00:33:52,316
and direct player feedback to drive iteration.

722
00:33:52,777 --> 00:33:54,758
But where that can start to fall down

723
00:33:55,319 --> 00:33:58,882
is when you have changes that you want to make

724
00:33:58,922 --> 00:34:01,224
that are really only for one group of players,

725
00:34:01,604 --> 00:34:03,666
and that group of players may actually be quite different

726
00:34:04,106 --> 00:34:06,608
than you expected or different than the group of players

727
00:34:06,628 --> 00:34:08,310
that's spending a lot of time giving you feedback.

728
00:34:09,098 --> 00:34:27,535
Tutorials and first time user experiences are notoriously difficult to optimize without using a data approach because designers and engaged players don't usually give great feedback on being a new player because they don't really remember what it was like to be a new player and it's difficult to give that mindset.

729
00:34:28,316 --> 00:34:34,681
You know, just to drive this home, this is some retention data from a game that I worked on and you can see.

730
00:34:35,502 --> 00:34:36,623
that it gets better over time.

731
00:34:36,863 --> 00:34:38,204
But what's really important is what we did

732
00:34:38,564 --> 00:34:40,245
to make this improvement happen.

733
00:34:40,686 --> 00:34:43,387
We started by just making basic updates to the game.

734
00:34:43,407 --> 00:34:44,328
We asked the design team,

735
00:34:44,348 --> 00:34:46,469
hey, could you improve the first time user experience?

736
00:34:46,790 --> 00:34:48,050
And they went in and they looked at it and they're like,

737
00:34:48,070 --> 00:34:49,311
well, these things are not that great

738
00:34:49,331 --> 00:34:50,892
and these things are not that great, we'll change them.

739
00:34:51,353 --> 00:34:52,313
And they did have an improvement.

740
00:34:52,333 --> 00:34:54,234
Like when we made those updates, it did actually help.

741
00:34:54,635 --> 00:34:55,655
But it didn't help that much.

742
00:34:56,056 --> 00:34:57,697
And we were sort of running into this problem

743
00:34:57,757 --> 00:34:58,998
over and over again where design was like,

744
00:34:59,018 --> 00:35:02,059
well, I don't really know what's gonna make a difference.

745
00:35:02,220 --> 00:35:04,261
And so then we added A-B testing.

746
00:35:05,177 --> 00:35:09,061
And A-B testing is just making a small change

747
00:35:09,661 --> 00:35:12,304
and having one group of players,

748
00:35:12,364 --> 00:35:14,686
that would be the A group, experience that change,

749
00:35:14,746 --> 00:35:16,087
and another group of players, the B group,

750
00:35:16,167 --> 00:35:17,288
not experience that change,

751
00:35:17,369 --> 00:35:18,450
or experience something different,

752
00:35:18,750 --> 00:35:19,891
and then see which one is better.

753
00:35:20,251 --> 00:35:21,532
And then whichever one performs better

754
00:35:21,652 --> 00:35:23,394
make that the final change.

755
00:35:23,474 --> 00:35:24,895
And so you can do this iteratively over time

756
00:35:24,916 --> 00:35:25,916
with very small things,

757
00:35:26,217 --> 00:35:28,199
and that can start to add up to big changes,

758
00:35:28,279 --> 00:35:29,320
as you can see in this graph.

759
00:35:29,520 --> 00:35:30,721
We really started to unlock.

760
00:35:31,094 --> 00:35:33,776
And this wasn't just doing exactly what the A B testing said.

761
00:35:34,057 --> 00:35:36,379
It was actually a combination of A B testing and design.

762
00:35:36,659 --> 00:35:38,500
Because as the A B test results came back,

763
00:35:38,801 --> 00:35:40,562
that helped the designers go,

764
00:35:40,582 --> 00:35:44,105
oh, this is really what's making a big difference.

765
00:35:44,205 --> 00:35:47,208
I'm going to focus on making great designs around that instead.

766
00:35:48,869 --> 00:35:53,773
So the next thing we can talk about in this optimizing phase is

767
00:35:54,472 --> 00:35:56,814
The idea of sort of machine learning.

768
00:35:56,854 --> 00:35:58,255
This is very popular right now,

769
00:35:58,355 --> 00:36:00,197
and a lot of times I talk to teams

770
00:36:00,217 --> 00:36:01,138
and they're like, yeah,

771
00:36:01,558 --> 00:36:03,300
I want to do a lot of multivariate testing.

772
00:36:03,340 --> 00:36:05,621
I really want to build a bunch of

773
00:36:05,681 --> 00:36:06,943
machine learning that's going to

774
00:36:07,303 --> 00:36:08,464
make those changes for me,

775
00:36:08,904 --> 00:36:09,985
and that is really cool.

776
00:36:10,025 --> 00:36:11,686
And if you work for a really big team

777
00:36:11,726 --> 00:36:13,408
with a lot of fantastic analytics

778
00:36:14,108 --> 00:36:15,570
available to you, you can do that.

779
00:36:15,790 --> 00:36:18,112
But I do want to say that you don't need that.

780
00:36:19,113 --> 00:36:20,734
You can actually get a lot done

781
00:36:21,154 --> 00:36:23,156
with pretty basic information.

782
00:36:23,683 --> 00:36:28,205
As an example, there's this example from MapleStory.

783
00:36:28,826 --> 00:36:31,227
So MapleStory, and this was quite a long time ago

784
00:36:31,287 --> 00:36:33,568
before we really had a lot of fancy machine learning at all.

785
00:36:34,569 --> 00:36:36,590
So this is actually one of my favorite examples.

786
00:36:36,610 --> 00:36:38,471
It's a system we introduced in MapleStory

787
00:36:38,791 --> 00:36:40,812
where when we saw players exhibit behaviors

788
00:36:40,832 --> 00:36:41,993
that correlated with churn,

789
00:36:42,013 --> 00:36:43,293
and this was pretty basic stuff,

790
00:36:43,333 --> 00:36:45,154
like logging in less frequently,

791
00:36:45,534 --> 00:36:46,895
leveling up less frequently,

792
00:36:46,915 --> 00:36:48,716
not talking to their friends as much.

793
00:36:49,865 --> 00:36:51,887
We would look at that behavior and we say,

794
00:36:52,027 --> 00:36:52,887
oh, if you're doing these things,

795
00:36:52,907 --> 00:36:54,048
you get a little flag on you.

796
00:36:55,089 --> 00:36:57,611
And then there's a chance that when you log out,

797
00:36:57,811 --> 00:36:58,952
you'll get this special message,

798
00:36:59,232 --> 00:36:59,992
which is basically,

799
00:37:00,092 --> 00:37:04,135
hey, if you log back in tomorrow or in the next three days,

800
00:37:04,375 --> 00:37:05,396
you're gonna get a free gift.

801
00:37:06,417 --> 00:37:08,138
And we didn't really worry about making

802
00:37:08,198 --> 00:37:09,959
churn prediction model perfectly accurate.

803
00:37:11,040 --> 00:37:13,581
We were really just trying to see if this would work

804
00:37:13,681 --> 00:37:16,083
with basic information about churn,

805
00:37:16,103 --> 00:37:17,104
just really obvious stuff.

806
00:37:19,030 --> 00:37:22,052
In fact, we actually eventually expanded this

807
00:37:22,552 --> 00:37:24,094
to allow the gift to trigger on accounts

808
00:37:24,134 --> 00:37:25,975
that didn't meet the term prediction criteria

809
00:37:26,275 --> 00:37:28,297
because the effect it was having was so positive.

810
00:37:28,697 --> 00:37:31,539
It was a really, really successful campaign.

811
00:37:31,639 --> 00:37:34,481
Players were actually really into this idea.

812
00:37:34,501 --> 00:37:36,423
They didn't really know why they would get the gift

813
00:37:36,463 --> 00:37:38,064
and there was a lot of conspiracy theories

814
00:37:38,084 --> 00:37:39,145
about what would get you the gift.

815
00:37:39,505 --> 00:37:41,807
And it just sort of generally increased retention

816
00:37:41,827 --> 00:37:43,108
across the board.

817
00:37:43,528 --> 00:37:46,030
And even though that's not what we think of

818
00:37:46,130 --> 00:37:48,672
super tight focused machine learning.

819
00:37:49,195 --> 00:37:51,797
algorithms that optimize everything.

820
00:37:52,037 --> 00:37:54,139
This was still a big benefit to the game

821
00:37:54,499 --> 00:37:56,201
and still really worthwhile to do.

822
00:37:56,321 --> 00:37:58,503
So I would say even if you don't have access

823
00:37:58,563 --> 00:38:01,385
to that kind of sophisticated machine learning,

824
00:38:01,405 --> 00:38:03,387
you can still try some things that can have

825
00:38:03,407 --> 00:38:04,608
a really positive effect.

826
00:38:05,389 --> 00:38:06,730
It's just important if you don't have

827
00:38:06,770 --> 00:38:07,991
that kind of sophisticated analytics

828
00:38:08,011 --> 00:38:09,672
to make sure that you do look

829
00:38:09,953 --> 00:38:11,514
and make sure it did have a positive effect

830
00:38:11,534 --> 00:38:12,395
and not a negative effect

831
00:38:12,435 --> 00:38:14,657
and then react to those changes accordingly.

832
00:38:14,677 --> 00:38:17,839
Okay, so we have the basics.

833
00:38:18,602 --> 00:38:21,264
And then we've added in this optimization

834
00:38:21,964 --> 00:38:25,987
where we've really focused on personalizing the experience

835
00:38:26,348 --> 00:38:29,290
and targeting offers and content to our players

836
00:38:29,310 --> 00:38:31,152
to like reduce risk

837
00:38:31,232 --> 00:38:33,213
and optimize individual player experience.

838
00:38:33,233 --> 00:38:34,734
So if you're doing both of these things

839
00:38:35,115 --> 00:38:38,037
and you're really having a lot of success already

840
00:38:38,457 --> 00:38:39,658
in getting these things done,

841
00:38:40,038 --> 00:38:42,480
we can move on to this final step

842
00:38:42,500 --> 00:38:44,582
where we add in the most sophisticated.

843
00:38:45,637 --> 00:38:48,978
LiveOps tactics, which is sort of called LiveOps mastery.

844
00:38:49,578 --> 00:38:51,959
And specifically, when I think about this step,

845
00:38:52,279 --> 00:38:54,640
the really the most advanced tactics for LiveOps,

846
00:38:55,000 --> 00:38:58,261
I think about expanding your game's engagement

847
00:38:58,641 --> 00:39:01,702
beyond the time players spend playing.

848
00:39:02,302 --> 00:39:04,183
At this phase, you should be thinking of your game

849
00:39:04,283 --> 00:39:07,324
as more than a collection of systems and content, right?

850
00:39:07,384 --> 00:39:09,685
Discussing the game, making fan art,

851
00:39:10,025 --> 00:39:11,386
reading tie-in comic books,

852
00:39:11,486 --> 00:39:12,566
meeting guild mates in real life.

853
00:39:13,111 --> 00:39:15,352
All of these are actually a part of your game,

854
00:39:16,312 --> 00:39:18,813
and they should be something that you care about designing.

855
00:39:18,833 --> 00:39:21,234
And that experience becomes vitally important

856
00:39:21,574 --> 00:39:23,934
as you move through this LiveOps journey.

857
00:39:24,275 --> 00:39:25,715
Because if you want to get to the place

858
00:39:25,755 --> 00:39:28,016
where you're strengthening your brand and your loyalty,

859
00:39:28,336 --> 00:39:31,497
and you actually start seeing organic growth and sustainment,

860
00:39:31,917 --> 00:39:34,838
i.e. not always having to pay for all your acquisition,

861
00:39:35,118 --> 00:39:36,358
you're going to have to focus on more

862
00:39:36,398 --> 00:39:38,339
than just what's happening inside of the game.

863
00:39:39,699 --> 00:39:40,640
While a lot of this work,

864
00:39:41,016 --> 00:39:43,137
happens quite literally outside of the game.

865
00:39:43,918 --> 00:39:45,619
Supportive integration with game systems

866
00:39:45,699 --> 00:39:47,701
is really what separates the best from the rest

867
00:39:47,781 --> 00:39:48,561
in this area.

868
00:39:48,581 --> 00:39:52,364
And it really behooves designers to think a lot

869
00:39:52,764 --> 00:39:54,846
about what these experiences are for their players,

870
00:39:54,966 --> 00:39:56,667
even outside of time spent in the game.

871
00:39:57,828 --> 00:39:59,409
Many of the examples for this phase,

872
00:39:59,429 --> 00:40:01,230
when we actually talk about systems in the game

873
00:40:01,270 --> 00:40:04,973
and not just outside community events and things like that,

874
00:40:05,313 --> 00:40:06,534
many of these examples are things

875
00:40:06,574 --> 00:40:07,975
that lots of games actually do,

876
00:40:08,075 --> 00:40:09,456
but very few do really well.

877
00:40:10,172 --> 00:40:12,033
An example I like to use is matchmaking.

878
00:40:12,873 --> 00:40:13,794
It's something that we've gotten

879
00:40:13,894 --> 00:40:15,395
really good at as an industry.

880
00:40:15,635 --> 00:40:17,296
If we define it as predicting who

881
00:40:17,336 --> 00:40:18,697
will win competitive matches,

882
00:40:19,157 --> 00:40:21,038
but we've struggled to really create

883
00:40:21,078 --> 00:40:22,519
matchmaking that predicts who will

884
00:40:22,559 --> 00:40:25,901
have fun together and so we actually

885
00:40:25,981 --> 00:40:27,842
ended up using matchmaking for something

886
00:40:27,882 --> 00:40:29,743
a lot more social in Guild Wars 2.

887
00:40:30,143 --> 00:40:31,584
I think is a really interesting

888
00:40:31,624 --> 00:40:33,145
example of this kind of.

889
00:40:34,225 --> 00:40:36,287
Thinking of engagement beyond

890
00:40:36,367 --> 00:40:37,327
just game systems.

891
00:40:38,182 --> 00:40:40,024
So I'm going to talk about Mega Servers,

892
00:40:40,064 --> 00:40:43,046
which is a whole program that we developed

893
00:40:43,367 --> 00:40:44,988
in Guild Wars 2 after the game had launched.

894
00:40:45,308 --> 00:40:46,329
But when the game launched,

895
00:40:46,909 --> 00:40:49,652
the way that Guild Wars 2 worked was players would log in

896
00:40:50,793 --> 00:40:53,855
and then they would tell us what map they wanted to go to.

897
00:40:54,296 --> 00:40:56,217
Right? In this case, Silverwaste,

898
00:40:56,237 --> 00:40:57,478
which is a map in Guild Wars 2.

899
00:40:58,199 --> 00:41:00,201
And then we would go, okay, you want to go to Silverwaste?

900
00:41:00,301 --> 00:41:02,142
Well, let's see if there's already

901
00:41:02,282 --> 00:41:03,683
a Silverwaste server up and running.

902
00:41:03,824 --> 00:41:04,884
Oh, there is, here it is.

903
00:41:05,445 --> 00:41:06,486
And there's an empty slot in it.

904
00:41:06,826 --> 00:41:07,347
So awesome.

905
00:41:07,790 --> 00:41:10,111
you will be moved into this server.

906
00:41:10,411 --> 00:41:12,171
And that was sort of the way it was supposed to work, right?

907
00:41:12,431 --> 00:41:14,572
Players would be sorted into the server until it was full.

908
00:41:15,132 --> 00:41:18,192
And then when it was full and another player showed up,

909
00:41:19,233 --> 00:41:20,173
they'd come along and say,

910
00:41:20,233 --> 00:41:22,013
hey, I want to go to Silverwaste.

911
00:41:22,093 --> 00:41:25,574
And we'd say, well, there's no room in Silverwaste,

912
00:41:25,634 --> 00:41:28,234
so we'll make a new version of Silverwaste for you.

913
00:41:29,054 --> 00:41:30,075
And you can go there.

914
00:41:30,715 --> 00:41:33,275
And then, you know, that one will eventually fill up too.

915
00:41:34,215 --> 00:41:35,896
And this all sounds pretty good on paper,

916
00:41:36,196 --> 00:41:36,396
but...

917
00:41:36,815 --> 00:41:38,457
In reality, when the game was live,

918
00:41:38,737 --> 00:41:41,619
what happened was we had a bunch of servers for maps,

919
00:41:42,099 --> 00:41:45,702
and then naturally players would empty out of those servers

920
00:41:45,922 --> 00:41:48,704
in a very organic, unorganized way.

921
00:41:49,305 --> 00:41:52,207
And eventually we would end up with sad,

922
00:41:52,307 --> 00:41:54,329
lonely players on an empty server

923
00:41:54,789 --> 00:41:57,131
with really no way to get more players in

924
00:41:57,211 --> 00:41:59,753
because they aren't the most recent server.

925
00:41:59,993 --> 00:42:01,734
And so when someone new comes to join,

926
00:42:02,175 --> 00:42:03,936
they would actually go to this server.

927
00:42:04,810 --> 00:42:07,231
that was most recently spun up instead of to the empty,

928
00:42:07,291 --> 00:42:08,832
lonely person above.

929
00:42:09,652 --> 00:42:14,173
Worse, we didn't really do anything to ensure

930
00:42:14,253 --> 00:42:15,934
that when a player joined your server,

931
00:42:15,994 --> 00:42:17,074
you were happy about it.

932
00:42:17,535 --> 00:42:20,996
And so in fact, sometimes players would not be happy

933
00:42:21,016 --> 00:42:22,716
about it, they wouldn't like the person

934
00:42:22,736 --> 00:42:24,797
that they were randomly paired with in their server

935
00:42:25,017 --> 00:42:28,378
and their, you know, enjoyment of the game would go down.

936
00:42:28,758 --> 00:42:30,879
So this led to a lot of inefficiencies,

937
00:42:30,919 --> 00:42:32,779
where you can see that this is also from a,

938
00:42:33,853 --> 00:42:35,933
services component incredibly inefficient.

939
00:42:36,233 --> 00:42:38,534
And so we decided we wanted to take

940
00:42:38,574 --> 00:42:40,074
a totally different approach to this.

941
00:42:41,055 --> 00:42:42,635
A lot of it was spurred by this idea

942
00:42:42,655 --> 00:42:44,156
of can we make this more efficient,

943
00:42:44,596 --> 00:42:47,236
but it quickly expanded to asking,

944
00:42:47,597 --> 00:42:49,697
can we make the game more enjoyable?

945
00:42:50,517 --> 00:42:53,198
So we changed everything about how we did this.

946
00:42:53,898 --> 00:42:55,419
Now when you log in, we would say,

947
00:42:55,479 --> 00:42:56,359
where do you want to go?

948
00:42:56,919 --> 00:42:58,920
But before we put you there,

949
00:42:59,160 --> 00:43:01,860
we'd ask you a whole lot of things about yourself.

950
00:43:03,091 --> 00:43:03,811
Are you in a guild?

951
00:43:04,231 --> 00:43:05,792
Have you played in a party recently?

952
00:43:06,092 --> 00:43:07,692
What kind of content do you like to play?

953
00:43:07,772 --> 00:43:09,293
What kind of play time do you usually have?

954
00:43:09,533 --> 00:43:10,053
What's your level?

955
00:43:10,073 --> 00:43:10,673
What's your class?

956
00:43:10,993 --> 00:43:12,314
What's the last map that you were in?

957
00:43:12,334 --> 00:43:14,114
And we've learned all these things about you

958
00:43:14,214 --> 00:43:16,095
and we had different weightings and we'd say, okay,

959
00:43:16,675 --> 00:43:18,435
now we know a little bit more about you.

960
00:43:18,475 --> 00:43:21,036
You're not just a random person, you're a specific person.

961
00:43:21,476 --> 00:43:23,337
And you want to go to Silverwaste, which is great.

962
00:43:23,657 --> 00:43:26,137
We actually have multiple Silverwaste servers open.

963
00:43:26,518 --> 00:43:28,738
Which one are you going to be the happiest on?

964
00:43:29,198 --> 00:43:29,358
Well,

965
00:43:29,945 --> 00:43:33,567
This is the one that we think you're going to fit the best with because of your play style,

966
00:43:33,607 --> 00:43:40,450
so you should go there. And this was took some learning, right? Like, you know, the waiting,

967
00:43:40,690 --> 00:43:44,172
we didn't, we had to make some guesses at first, and then we had to optimize that over time.

968
00:43:44,492 --> 00:43:50,955
We also made some fairly large mistakes early on. For instance, the first version of this

969
00:43:51,095 --> 00:43:55,277
sorting algorithm just straight up didn't ask what language you spoke.

970
00:43:55,710 --> 00:44:01,371
And it turns out that sorting people into servers with a bunch of people who don't speak their language makes them pretty unhappy.

971
00:44:01,391 --> 00:44:12,574
That was fairly easy to fix, right? We started, we added the language option in pretty quickly, and that was very heavily weighted because even if you would get along really well with a server full of people,

972
00:44:12,914 --> 00:44:16,955
if none of them speak Spanish, you're probably actually not going to have that great of a time.

973
00:44:17,035 --> 00:44:20,275
So we might actually find out that maybe you do match.

974
00:44:20,615 --> 00:44:21,816
The first server here a little better,

975
00:44:22,056 --> 00:44:23,117
but we're going to put you up here

976
00:44:23,297 --> 00:44:24,678
because that's where people are

977
00:44:24,698 --> 00:44:25,638
going to be speaking your language,

978
00:44:25,658 --> 00:44:26,599
and that makes a big difference.

979
00:44:27,620 --> 00:44:28,320
This effort,

980
00:44:29,061 --> 00:44:32,223
which was driven by engineering and design,

981
00:44:33,104 --> 00:44:35,105
ultimately just really improved the

982
00:44:35,145 --> 00:44:36,266
social experience in the game in

983
00:44:36,306 --> 00:44:37,847
general and we had we had general

984
00:44:37,948 --> 00:44:41,210
uplift in player engagement and

985
00:44:41,250 --> 00:44:43,211
retention and and you know I don't know.

986
00:44:43,231 --> 00:44:44,653
It might be overstating a little bit,

987
00:44:44,713 --> 00:44:46,214
but as our game matured,

988
00:44:46,294 --> 00:44:49,216
I think this system really helped.

989
00:44:49,713 --> 00:44:55,597
the game grow and thrive after it got over that initial excitement of launch

990
00:44:55,657 --> 00:44:58,479
and really became more about a continual community.

991
00:45:00,460 --> 00:45:07,264
Such as one example of using in-game systems to drive the kind of social

992
00:45:07,304 --> 00:45:10,546
behavior we want that can extend outside of the game itself.

993
00:45:11,346 --> 00:45:14,648
Another one is to think about community events.

994
00:45:15,409 --> 00:45:18,150
When we think about community, a lot of times designers think about

995
00:45:18,563 --> 00:45:20,925
you know, forum moderation and fan meetups,

996
00:45:21,305 --> 00:45:23,766
but communities really form and thrive

997
00:45:24,446 --> 00:45:25,747
because they have something to talk about.

998
00:45:25,827 --> 00:45:27,468
And that usually actually comes from the game itself.

999
00:45:27,908 --> 00:45:30,189
And so sometimes we actually want to create content

1000
00:45:30,209 --> 00:45:32,410
that's about making a community moment

1001
00:45:33,410 --> 00:45:37,692
and not just about driving playtime or increasing revenue,

1002
00:45:38,013 --> 00:45:39,793
but it's really just about getting players

1003
00:45:39,834 --> 00:45:41,274
something cool and exciting to do.

1004
00:45:41,294 --> 00:45:44,056
So one of my favorite events we ever ran in MapleStory

1005
00:45:44,096 --> 00:45:46,177
was the Random Beauty Coupon Drop event.

1006
00:45:47,210 --> 00:45:50,071
So we have these random beauty coupons

1007
00:45:50,131 --> 00:45:51,852
you can buy in MapleStory.

1008
00:45:52,373 --> 00:45:53,774
And they were this consumable item.

1009
00:45:54,254 --> 00:45:55,234
And when you use them,

1010
00:45:55,254 --> 00:45:57,476
they would change your appearance totally randomly.

1011
00:45:57,496 --> 00:45:59,377
You get a random face, random hair,

1012
00:45:59,657 --> 00:46:01,118
random skin tone, random eyes.

1013
00:46:01,478 --> 00:46:02,459
All these would be random.

1014
00:46:03,079 --> 00:46:04,820
This was not a very popular item

1015
00:46:04,860 --> 00:46:06,081
because it was truly random.

1016
00:46:06,401 --> 00:46:08,262
And there was hundreds of appearance options.

1017
00:46:08,302 --> 00:46:10,403
So you can end up with something pretty funky

1018
00:46:10,463 --> 00:46:12,624
as a pretty significant roll of the dice.

1019
00:46:14,385 --> 00:46:15,186
So they weren't that popular.

1020
00:46:15,206 --> 00:46:16,167
We didn't sell that many of them.

1021
00:46:16,428 --> 00:46:19,109
But we decided it would be fun to run this event

1022
00:46:19,570 --> 00:46:21,751
where we dropped them commonly

1023
00:46:21,891 --> 00:46:23,372
off of all the monsters in the game.

1024
00:46:23,812 --> 00:46:25,453
So now when the players were playing,

1025
00:46:26,093 --> 00:46:27,594
they would defeat an enemy

